<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="description">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Morphological description.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
Cells cylindrical, valve face flat, 7.5-12.8 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
in diameter, valve mantle 3.8-4.7 
<normalizedToken originalValue="μm">μm</normalizedToken>
high. Valve face with rough areolae, located in intersecting diagonal rows (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. LM (A, B) and SEM (C-H) images of species found in the transitional zone at Mykolaiv city: A Aulacoseira islandica, valve view B Aulacoseira nivalis, valve view C Aulacoseira subarctica, girdle view of complete frustule D-H Actinocyclus normanii valve view (D pseudonodulus shown with arrow, E, G) and girdle view (H, F). Scale bars: 10 μm." figureDoi="10.3897/phytokeys.178.64426.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/545735" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">3B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="ecology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Ecology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
This is a freshwater species, found growing in or near snow and in alpine pools (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1080/0269249X.2007.9705695" author="Houk, V" journalOrPublisher="Diatom Research" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="57 - 80" refId="B59" refString="Houk, V, Klee, R, Passauer, U, 2007. Observations on taxa of Melosira sensu lato among the slides from the Grunow diatom collection in Vienna (Austria). Part 1. Diatom Research 22 (1): 57 - 80, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1080/0269249X.2007.9705695" title="Observations on taxa of Melosira sensu lato among the slides from the Grunow diatom collection in Vienna (Austria). Part 1." url="https://doi.org/10.1080/0269249X.2007.9705695" volume="22" year="2007">Houk et al. 2007</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1635/053.158.0102" author="English, J" journalOrPublisher="Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="37 - 48" refId="B26" refString="English, J, Potapova, M, 2009. Aulacoseira pardata sp. nov., A. nivalis comb. nov., A. nivaloides comb. et stat. nov., and their occurrences in western North America. Proceedings. Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia 158 (1): 37 - 48, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1635/053.158.0102" title="Aulacoseira pardata sp. nov., A. nivalis comb. nov., A. nivaloides comb. et stat. nov., and their occurrences in western North America. Proceedings." url="https://doi.org/10.1635/053.158.0102" volume="158" year="2009">English and Potapova 2009</bibRefCitation>
) but was also reported for alkaline and acid waters (
<bibRefCitation author="Kulikovskiy, M" journalOrPublisher="Filigran, Yaroslavl" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B78" refString="Kulikovskiy, M, Glushchenko, AM, Kuznetsova, IV, Genkal, SI, 2016. [Identification book of diatoms from Russia]. Filigran, Yaroslavl" title="[Identification book of diatoms from Russia]." year="2016">Kulikovskiy et al. 2016</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
At the localities of upstream Mykolaiv, in Mykolaiv City and downstream Mykolaiv 
<taxonomicName authority="" authorityName="" class="Coscinodiscophyceae" family="Aulacoseiraceae" genus="Aulacoseira" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Aulacoseira nivalis" order="Aulacoseirales" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Bacillariophyta" rank="species" species="nivalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Aulacoseira nivalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the first record for Ukraine (Table 
<tableCitation captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="T1" captionText="Table 1. Species composition of centric diatoms at the investigated sites near Mykolaiv city in the Southern Bug River in the year 2017 (2013 added for station 2)." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DD3AC92F3D14B9FD95B22148C16CA677" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" tableUuid="DD3AC92F3D14B9FD95B22148C16CA677">1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
As for other countries, it is known from alpine and northern regions (
<bibRefCitation author="Krammer, K" journalOrPublisher="Spektrum Akademischer Verlag, Heidelberg, Berlin" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B75" refString="Krammer, K, Lange-Bertalot, H, 2000. Bacillariophyceae. Bd. 2., Teil 3: Centrales, Fragilariaceae, Eunotiaceae. Suesswasserflora von Mitteleuropa. Spektrum Akademischer Verlag, Heidelberg, Berlin" title="Bacillariophyceae. Bd. 2., Teil 3: Centrales, Fragilariaceae, Eunotiaceae. Suesswasserflora von Mitteleuropa." year="2000">Krammer and Lange-Bertalot 2000</bibRefCitation>
); frequently occurring in western North America (
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.1635/053.158.0102" author="English, J" journalOrPublisher="Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" pagination="37 - 48" refId="B26" refString="English, J, Potapova, M, 2009. Aulacoseira pardata sp. nov., A. nivalis comb. nov., A. nivaloides comb. et stat. nov., and their occurrences in western North America. Proceedings. Academy of Natural Sciences of Philadelphia 158 (1): 37 - 48, DOI: https://doi.org/10.1635/053.158.0102" title="Aulacoseira pardata sp. nov., A. nivalis comb. nov., A. nivaloides comb. et stat. nov., and their occurrences in western North America. Proceedings." url="https://doi.org/10.1635/053.158.0102" volume="158" year="2009">English and Potapova 2009</bibRefCitation>
) and as being abundant in lake sediments in Brazil.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
